"1376","1310":"1310","about 1310":"circa 1310","about 1330":"circa 1330","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Frodesley, Shropshire, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, England","Acton Scott, Church Stretton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Acton Scott, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1310–":"about 1310–Deceased","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1326–Female":"1326–Deceased","1328–Female":"1328–Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1311–1333":"1311–1333","1334–1376":"1334–1376","–Male":"Deceased","1294–Male":"1294–Deceased","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1294":"1294","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1334":"1334","1300":"1300","1333":"1333","1311":"1311","1376":"1376","1310":"1310","about 1310":"about 1310","about 1330":"about 1330","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Frodesley, Shropshire, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, England","Acton Scott, Church Stretton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Acton Scott, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Collins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Colin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish and Manx: shortened Anglicized from <b>Ó Coileáin</b>, compare   Cullen  , or in Man or west Ulster shortened from <b>Mac Coileáin</b>, compare   McQuillan   and   McCallion  . The genitival <i>-s</i> is a local addition to   Collin   and variants after the surname was Anglicized.","Americanized form of French   Colin   or   Collin   and also   Collette  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Alfredo, Francisco, Jesus, Ricardo, Alberto, Angel, Arturo, Eduardo, Esteban, Faustino.  French Alexandre, Andre, Armand, Georges, Henri, Jean Claude, Jean-Michel, Laurette, Lucien, Marcel, Patrice, Pierre.","French, Walloon, and Breton: from a French shortened pet form of the personal name   Nicolas   (see   Nicholas  ). This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","English: from the personal name <i>Colin</i>, a diminutive of <i>Col</i>, itself a pet form of   Nicholas  ."]},{"name":"Kolenc","meanings":["Slovenian:","topographic name derived from <i>koleno</i> ‘knee’.","nickname from the dialect plant name <i>kolenc</i> ‘yellow bedstraw (Galium verum)’ or ‘common nipplewort (Lapsana communis)’. Compare   Collins   3."]},{"name":"Callins","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Collins  ."]},{"name":"Collings","meanings":["English: variant of   Collins   or   Colling  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Aline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["In the Middle Ages this represented a contracted form of   Adeline .  In modern use it is either a revival of this or a respelling of   Aileen .  In Scotland and Ireland it has sometimes been chosen as representing an Anglicized spelling of the Gaelic vocabulary word <i>àlainn</i> (Scottish), <i>álainn</i> (Irish), meaning ‘lovely’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","descri